<div id="banner">
	<h1>The Numbers Don&#8217;t Lie</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>Lessig is fond of saying copyright has been extended &#8220;eleven times in the past forty years&#8221;. This is true, but a much stronger case can be made: <strong>copyright has been extended for forty years over the past forty years</strong>. How many acts were passed doesn&#8217;t seem so important&#8212;the key point is that the term of copyright keeps going up. Here&#8217;s the proof:</p>

<p><img src="../2002/copychart" alt="Chart of Copyright Extensions over Time" align="left"/><strong>Year: Length (Difference) Mickey&#8217;s Age (Difference)</strong><br />
1790: 28<br />
1909: 42 (14)<br />
1962: 56 (14) 35 (21)<br />
1965: 59 (3) 38 (21)<br />
1967: 61 (2) 40 (21)<br />
1968: 62 (1) 41 (21)<br />
1970: 64 (2) 43 (21)<br />
1971: 65 (1) 44 (21)<br />
1972: 67 (2) 45 (22)<br />
1974: 69 (2) 47 (22)<br />
1976: 85 (16) 49 (36)<br />
1992: 90 (5) 65 (25)<br />
1997: 95 (5) 70 (25)<br /><br clear="all" /></p><p>I&#8217;ve also plotted the age of Mickey Mouse (the straight dark line). As you can see, copyright lengths go up as soon as Mickey gets a little too close to freedom, ensuring that Mickey&#8217;s eternally &#8220;20 years away&#8221; from entering the Public Domain. </p>

<p>Thanks to Zooko for suggesting I plot Mickey and Bill Coltire for his superb <a href="http://www.title17.com/">Hypertext Annotated Title 17</a> which made this possible.</p>

